 characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Carmino, Domenico, Luciano, Nicola.","Italian: altered form of <b>Mabilia</b>, from the old female personal name <i>Mabile</i>, from Latin <i>Amabilis</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hatley","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which derives from a place name, probably Hailey in Oxfordshire, which was originally named from Old English <i>hēg</i> ‘hay’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘clearing’. Use as a given name began in the 1960s, inspired perhaps by the actress  Hayley Mills  (  b. 1946 ), daughter of  Sir John Mills  and  Mary Hayley Bell , and enjoyed great popularity until the late 1990s."],"variants":[{"name":"Haylee","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which derives from a place name, probably Hailey in Oxfordshire, which was originally named from Old English <i>hēg</i> ‘hay’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘clearing’. Use as a given name began in the 1960s, inspired perhaps by the actress  Hayley Mills  (  b. 1946 ), daughter of  Sir John Mills  and  Mary Hayley Bell , and enjoyed great popularity until the late 1990s."]},{"name":"Haleigh","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which derives from a place name, probably Hailey in Oxfordshire, which was originally named from Old English <i>hēg</i> ‘hay’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘clearing’. Use as a given name began in the 1960s, inspired perhaps by the actress  Hayley Mills  (  b. 1946 ), daughter of  Sir John Mills  and  Mary Hayley Bell , and enjoyed great popularity until the late 1990s."]},{"name":"Haley","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Hayley ."]},{"name":"Hallie","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Hayley ."]},{"name":"Hailey","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Hayley ."]},{"name":"Hailee","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which derives from a place name, probably Hailey in Oxfordshire, which was originally named from Old English <i>hēg</i> ‘hay’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘clearing’. Use as a given name began in the 1960s, inspired perhaps by the actress  Hayley Mills  (  b. 1946 ), daughter of  Sir John Mills  and  Mary Hayley Bell , and enjoyed great popularity until the late 1990s."]}]},{"name":"St.","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Cornish: A Cornish form of Just (Prouter Est, the priest of St. Just)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":65,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":74,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":109,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Mabilia of Hatley St. George was born about 1150, in Hatley St George, Cambridgeshire, England, her father, William de St. George, was 21 and her mother, Bancis, was 22. She married William de St. George before 1170, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1150–":"umbes 1150–Surnud","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1180–1223":"1180–1223","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","1130":"1130","before 1170":"enne 1170","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","Hatley St George, Cambridgeshire, England":"Hatley St George, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1150–":"noin 1150–Kuollut","1150–Female":"1150–Kuollut","1180–1223":"1180–1223","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1170–M